d, whether primarily natural or technological, are a complex cacophony that is desperately trying to tell us something about the rapidly failing health of the planet and its inhabitants. As Pettman cautions, we would do well to listen.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aListening (Philosophy). 0aSound (Philosophy). 0aVoice (Philosophy). 4aanimal studies. 4acreaturely life. 4acritical theory. 4aecology. 4aenvironmental humanities. 4amedia theory. 4aphilosophy of technology. 4aposthumanities. 4asound studies. 4avoice. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Phenomenology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311070369640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360148240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503601482423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503601482.jpg  a978-3-11-070369-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles